is arrangement, the U.S. government violated its agreements with allies in the developed world. Spiro argues that American policymakers took this action to prop up otherwise intolerable levels of U.S. public debt. In effect, recycled OPEC wealth subsidized the debt-happy policies of the U.S. government as well as the debt-happy consumption of its citizenry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBalance of paymentszArab countries. 0aInternational finance. 0aInvestments, Arab. 0aPetroleum productsxPrices. 4aInternational Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171197840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501711978423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501711978.jpg  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK